## When to Use `useStore` vs `useQuery`/`useMutation`

When a DataSource exists for the entity, prefer `useStore` for any page that **edits** data. It eliminates manual state management (no `useState` for local edits, no `useRef` for server snapshots, no equality comparisons for change detection). The store gives you dirty tracking, `save()`, and `resetStore()` for free.

| Scenario | Use | Why |
|----------|-----|-----|
| CRUD with dirty tracking (edit/save/cancel) | `useStore` | Automatic change detection, batch save, revert on cancel |
| Multiple related stores saving together | `useStore` + `Promise.all([a.save(), b.save()])` | Parallel save, unified dirty state |
| Read-only views with computed/joined data | `useQuery` | DataSource can't do JOINs or computed columns |
| One-off operations that navigate away | `useMutation` | Delete, duplicate — no local state to track |
| Updating sharing/permissions on an entity | `useStore` + `updateRow()` + `save()` | Avoids a separate mutation; changes flow through one mechanism |

**Example — dashboard detail page:**
- `useStore<Dashboards>` for layout, visibility, sharing (owner edits)
- `useStore<DashboardWidgets>` for widget content (both save together)
- `useQuery('getMyDashboards')` for list page (needs computed `widgetCount` JOIN)
- `useMutation('deleteDashboard')` for delete (navigates away)

---

## Alias Naming Convention

Use consistent, descriptive alias names:

| Pattern | Use Case | Example |
|---------|----------|---------|
| `{module}-list` | List pages | `users-list`, `projects-list` |
| `{module}-edit` | Edit pages/forms | `user-edit`, `project-edit` |
| `{module}-dialog` | Dialogs | `user-dialog`, `add-project-dialog` |
| `{module}-combobox` | Lookup/combobox data | `user-combobox`, `role-combobox` |
| `{module}-{context}` | Specific contexts | `user-roles-tab`, `project-tasks-panel` |

